div.p:
With a rational design of multiple reaction steps, researchers now suggest a new perspective on the “carving” of the nanostructures in a desired manner [

 10

]. The Galvanic replacement reaction and the Kirkendall effect were simultaneously applied for the synthesis of complex metal nanoboxes with multiple walls [

 11

]. Ouyang and co-workers established a universal method to yield metal–semiconductor core–shell nanoparticles via a sequential process of chalcogenization and cation exchange reactions using sacrificial Ag shells on metal cores [

 12

]. Asymmetric metal–semiconductor heterodimers were also prepared using similar protocols [

 13

].

The design of double shell hollow nanostructures has another clear advantage to enhance photocatalytic stability. Amirav and Alivisatos reported that the effective separation of reduction and oxidation sites in the CdSe/CdS nanorods decorated with Pt significantly enhanced both photocatalytic activity and selectivity [

 24

]. Li and co-workers introduced dual co-catalysts on CdS/ZnS core–shell nanoparticles for the separation of reaction sites, which exhibited high activities [

 25

]. In the metal–semiconductor double shell hollow structure, the reduction sites on the metal layers are exposed inward, and the oxidation sites of the semiconductor layers are exposed outward, which provide complete separation of the counter reactions. Consequently, the unwanted reactions such as photochemical corrosion of the metal–semiconductor interface would be completely blocked. For instance, the Pt–CdS double shell hollow nanocubes exhibited high activity and stability on photocatalytic hydrogen evolution [

 26

].

To combine multiple nanoscale reactions, Ag is one of the best materials among transition metal compositions. For the control of morphology, Ag cubes can be converted into hollow cubes with noble metal ions bearing high electrochemical potentials by the Galvanic replacement reaction. For the control of compositions, Ag readily reacts with selenourea to yield silver selenides in the presence of oxygen in air. As a next step, the cation exchange reaction can vary the cationic compositions to yield proper metal selenides. These sequential reaction processes seem to work well; however, each reaction step must be carefully optimized with the consideration of both morphology and composition changes. For instance, the Galvanic replacement should be quenched at a certain degree of the reaction; otherwise a dealloying process occurs to destruct the regular hollow structure [

 28

]. The selenization reaction must be fully proceeded for the effective conversion of components by cation exchange at the next step. Through the precise adjustment of the reaction conditions in each reaction step, the uniform metal–semiconductor double shell hollow nanocubes can be obtained in a high yield.

These photocatalytic hydrogen evolution data suggest that the double shell hollow structure is an excellent photocatalyst structure in several reasons: The semiconductor outer shells effectively receives photons, and the resulting photogenerated electrons are transferred to the metal inner shells through the well-defined interface. The spatial separation of the reduction reaction on the inward metal surface and the oxidation reaction on the outward semiconductor provides superior stability to suppress the interface oxidation, as well as high activity [

 26

].
